summary: Crowdcast: Reproductive Rights on the 50th Anniversary of Roe
description: January would’ve marked the 50th anniversary of Roe v. Wade, the landmark Supreme Court decision that made abortion a constitutionally protected right. That decision stood for 49 years — impacting generations of women and giving millions of people greater autonomy over their reproductive rights — until the high court overturned it in June. The 19th will mark January’s consequential milestone with high-level conversations on the legal, historical and cultural impact of Roe, and what the future holds without it.

summary: How To Talk About Abortion: December Lunch & Learn
description:
This month, we will be discussing how to talk about abortion. Our Abortion Stigma Lunch & Learn in July was both well attended and well received, so we have decided to widen the topic and continue the conversation this month.

As we head into the holiday season, it's likely that you'll be sitting across the table from loved ones who share different views from you. If you are interested in engaging in conversation with them about abortion, Roe v. Wade and other topics related to reproductive rights, you'll definitely want to join us for this one.

Now that Roe has been overturned, the landscape of abortion access across the country will dramatically shift for the worse. Many states have already restricted or outright banned abortion. Millions of people, but especially young people, Black, Indigenous, People of Color, low-income people, and people living in rural communities will be most impacted by this decision.

Join Our Post-Roe World Explained — a virtual town hall presented by the United State of Women, Planned Parenthood Federation of America and partners on Tuesday, July 19th at 7pm ET. We’ll share concrete actions you can take to advocate for abortion access in your community and reproductive justice for all.

Hi there! Thanks for signing up for “Our Post-Roe World Explained”, a virtual town hall on abortion access.

summary: Make Calls to Voters Of Color with Georgia Coalition for the People’s Agenda
description:
DEADLINE TO SIGN UP IS 4PM ET THE DAY BEFORE YOUR SHIFT.

Note: Special phone bank “launches” with special guests including Ms. Helen Butler and other notable speakers TBA will take place at 2pm ET on Wednesday, November 16, Tuesday, November 22, Tuesday, November 29 and Monday, December 5 at 2pm.  

The Georgia Senate run-off is on December 6. Voters in Georgia have faced historic voter suppression aimed at disenfranchising voters of color.  

In fact, the very existence of the Senate runoff election in Georgia comes from a history of the state intentionally implementing laws and policies to dilute the voting power of communities of color.

That’s why we’re making calls to voters in Georgia every day from 2-7pm ET starting Wednesday, November 16 going through December 6 to make sure they are registered and have a plan to vote.

It’s essential that we call under-represented voters to make sure they check their voter registration, request their mail-in ballots, and bring an acceptable voter ID so that no one gets turned away from the polls.
Together, we can finish the job we started by ensuring every person is able to participate in our Democracy.

https://www.mobilize.us/voterempowerment/event/543478/

Description: Anti-choice groups filed a federal lawsuit in a Texas district court challenging the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) in its decades-old approval of mifepristone, one of the two medications typically used to provide medication abortion care. The lawsuit seeks to revoke the FDA’s approval of mifepristone in an attempt to effectively ban medication abortion nationwide. A federal ruling means health care providers would be banned from prescribing mifepristone for medication abortion and miscarriage treatment, no matter where you live. 

We are currently expecting the ruling to come down on or around Friday, February 24th. During this webinar on the following Monday night, the panel of speakers, moderated by Jessica Mason Pieklo (Rewire News), will discuss what this ruling means for abortion access, what's next, and how you can make your voice heard.

### Get up to speed about the current and potential legal status of reproductive freedom, and what we can do to help!

Medication abortion is under attack from MAGA-Republicans, who won't stop at overturning Roe v. Wade. They are actively working toward banning abortion nationwide — including by trying to block access to mifepristone, one of two medications most commonly used in medication abortion.

A lawsuit in the Northern District of Texas could result in a devastating nationwide ban on mifepristone — even in states where abortion is protected — with a decision coming down any day. 

The good news is, there are actions we can take right now to defend choice! State judicial systems are the front lines of this fight, and there is an important state Supreme Court election coming up in Wisconsin.

Join the United State of Women for our Volunteer Month of Action for Abortion Access! Each week, you will get trained on how to use digital organizing strategies to help you get involved in the fight for abortion access. Deepen your activism today and join our movement of abortion advocates fighting for a world where all people have access to the care that they need.

### Here are the actions we’ll be taking for each week:
- Training #1: Spread the word about self-managed abortion (Registration for this session will close on June 13, 6pm ET)

- Training #2: Spread the word about the Women’s Health Protection Act (Registration for this session will close on June 20, 6pm ET)

- Training #3: Community care and how to be an abortion advocate (Registration for this session will close on June 27, 6pm ET)

*Note: To ensure that volunteers who participate in this volunteer opportunity are aligned with our values around access to abortion, we will be asking registrants to share a link to help verify your identity online. This can be a social media account, LinkedIn profile, or any other webpage with your name on it. We appreciate your understanding as we aim to build a safe environment for our volunteers.

How to prepare:
Hi there! Thank you for signing up for USOW’s Volunteer Month of Action for Abortion Access! We will gather to learn more about why we’re here today, and then get started with a mini training session. Afterwards, we will play music and hang out together while we take action for abortion access.

### Here are the actions we’ll be taking for each week:
- Training #1: Spread the word about self-managed abortion
- Training #2: Spread the word about the Women’s Health Protection Act
- Training #3: Community care and how to be an abortion advocate

Zoom instructions will be sent the day of each training session.

Now that you’ve signed up, invite 3 friends or family members to join you by sharing this link! https://www.mobilize.us/usow/event/564986/?utm_source=volunteer

summary: Self-Managed Abortion On Our Own Terms: Communities of Color & Criminalization
description:
Link to join: https://www.mobilize.us/join/23504469/1:e0c51c2b285333bced0432748c46fce963341e7282991b5593a0a2fdbf501926/

Currently, only two states, South Carolina and Nevada, criminalize self-managed abortions, yet people continue to be reported to authorities for self-managing even when there are no existing criminalization laws in their state. The communities who are most likely to self-manage – people of color, immigrants, people living in poverty, and LGBTQ+ communities – are at an increased risk for criminalization and surveillance. These communities are already disproportionately targeted by police due to their intersecting identities.

Join speakers from the United State of Women, Miscarriage and Abortion Hotline, and If/When/How: Lawyering for Reproductive Justice on Wednesday, July 19th at 6pm ET for Self-Managed Abortion On Our Own Terms: Communities of Color & Criminalization to learn more about the way communities of color are impacted by the criminalization of self-managed abortion. This webinar will cover the barriers communities of color face when accessing reproductive healthcare, data around the criminalization of self-managed abortion, how a person's intersecting identities can make them vulnerable to an increased risk of prosecution, the current legal landscape, and ways you can help your community avoid criminalization.

A huge thank you to our amplification partners for making sure this event reached as many people as possible, we could not do this work without you: Abortion Access Front, Abortion Action Missouri, Abortion Freedom Fund, Collective Power for Reproductive Justice, Desert Star Institute for Family Planning, End Rape On Campus, Esperanza United, Forward Midwifery, Frontera Fund, If/When/How: Lawyering for Reproductive Justice, Ipas, Just the Pill | Abortion Delivered, Justice for Migrant Women, NARAL Pro-Choice America, National Council of Jewish Women, National Institute for Reproductive Health, National Latina Institute for Reproductive Justice, National Partnership for Women & Families, National Organization for Women, New Mexico Religious Coalition for Reproductive Choice, NOISE FOR NOW, Physicians for Reproductive Health, Pills By Post, Plan C, Pregnancy Justice, Red State Access, Reproaction, RH Impact, Supermajority, The Afiya Center, The Women's Centers, UltraViolet, URGE : Unite for Reproductive & Gender Equity, We Testify, Women's March and YWCA USA.

location: Northwest Health Foundation, 221 NW 2nd Ave #300, Portland, OR 97209, USA
description:
The 2024 Boot-CAMPaign for Change Series is almost here! We are so excited to be facilitating this program, and want to make sure that you have everything you need to be successful. With that in mind, here's some information about the sessions:


We will be providing dinner on Thursday, as well as a light breakfast and lunch on both Saturdays. 

Bringing a laptop with you is not necessary to participate in the program, but is encouraged! We will also have pen and paper if that is how you prefer to take notes.


Please see below for instructions on how to access the building, as well as the building’s accessibility information.

Elevator Access Code: The elevator access code for our gathering will be 49217#. You must enter the five-digit number AND # (on the bottom right of the keypad), and then press the elevator floor button for the 3rd floor to make the elevator go up. You will need to enter the code outside the elevator and inside the elevator, in addition to the lobby doors.

Accessing the Building: Boot-CAMP will be hosted at the Northwest Health Foundation (NWHF)  in Portland and will be facilitated in English. There are two accessible entrances to NWHF with ADA door openers: one on NW 2nd Ave and one through the parking lot on NW 3rd Ave. There is an elevator and stairs in the lobby which will take you to the meeting space. There is one single-user restroom and one all-user restroom on the floor. Seating in the meeting rooms is primarily cushioned, rolling chairs with arm rests. If you need any chairs without armrests, please let us know.

COVID: Masks are encouraged but not required in the building. We ask that all meeting attendees adhere to current CDC guidance if they have recently tested positive for or been exposed to COVID-19. Hand sanitizer and surface sanitizing stations are available throughout the building. 

Other Building Details: There are two Narcan doses and two CPR masks on each floor of the building. The building has a fragrance-free policy.  Please don’t wear perfume, cologne, aftershave, scented lotion, essential oils or other fragrances. With that in mind, we also recognize that fragrances are an important part of many cultural or religious practices. For this reason, please let me know directly if you would like us to consider an exception to this policy.

Getting to Northwest Health Foundation: The entrance is located on NW 2nd Ave. Look for the double doors under the awning labeled “The Thomas Aschenbrener Center for Philanthropy.”

description:
Please RSVP: https://secure.everyaction.com/0yS7x6ZuQEm77k6q_xjfbQ2


Tuesday, November 26th from 5:30-7:30pm
White Owl Social Club (1305 SE 8th Ave, Portland, OR 97214)

Please join Oregon Futures Lab (OFL) for the 2024 OFL Election Graduation! We would love for folks to join us for happy hour to celebrate your own and each other's achievements, network with a community of like-minded people and maybe pick up a tip or suggestion for folks thinking about their post-election job search.


Accessibility
COVID Precautions: If you are feeling ill or have had recent exposure to COVID, we ask that you please stay home to keep our community members safe. Masks are not required, but hand sanitizer and disposable masks will be available for guests.

Building access: Please enter at the main entrance through the bar (note: this is a 21+ over event). Wheelchair access is available through a gate adjacent to the patio, which White Owl staff will need to open. Please let OFL know if you require this entrance (email naomi@oregonfutureslab.org). There are gender neutral sit/stand restrooms. There is an ADA accessible restroom available upon request.

Parking and public transportation: Street parking is available and ample. The building can be reached by many TriMet bus lines and is located at the corner of SE 8th Ave and SE Main St. Get help planning your trip at http://trimet.org/#/planner.

Photography: OFL staff will be taking photos of this event.

Email naomi@oregonfutureslab.org with any questions or concerns.
